{"ops":[{"insert":"WareWoolf"},{"attributes":{"align":"center","header":1},"insert":"\n"},{"insert":"\nWareWoolf is designed for one thing: writing fiction. It is intentionally simplified: you cannot change the font, line spacing, or color. But it has everything you need to organize, edit, and revise a novel.\n\nIt is composed of three simple text-based panels with no icons: Chapters, Editor, and Notes. \n\nThat's it. There is no toolbar with twenty buttons cluttering the screen. There isn't even a file menu unless you summon it. All formatting is done with shortcuts. (But don't worry, there aren't many to memorize, and you can always press "},{"attributes":{"bold":true},"insert":"CTRL"},{"insert":" + "},{"attributes":{"bold":true},"insert":"H"},{"insert":" to show them all in the Shortcut Helper. And it's not like you do a lot of formatting when writing fiction anyway.)\n"},{"attributes":{"header":2},"insert":"\n"},{"insert":"Display Controls"},{"attributes":{"header":2},"insert":"\n"},{"insert":"On the left is the list of chapters, which you can re-order and rename. In the middle, the main editor. On the right, notes. These three panels can each be toggled on/off with "},{"attributes":{"bold":true},"insert":"F1"},{"insert":", "},{"attributes":{"bold":true},"insert":"F2"},{"insert":", and "},{"attributes":{"bold":true},"insert":"F3"},{"insert":", so you can clear everything but the editor for a fully distraction-free experience, or make room for using a narrow vertical screen.\n\nSpeaking of room--the editor panel can be contracted or expanded using "},{"attributes":{"bold":true},"insert":"CTRL"},{"insert":" + "},{"attributes":{"bold":true},"insert":"<"},{"insert":" or "},{"attributes":{"bold":true},"insert":">"},{"insert":" so you can see your paragraphs as they will look in a narrow paperback or a wide manuscript page. Similarly, you can adjust the font display size with "},{"attributes":{"bold":true},"insert":"CTRL"},{"insert":" + "},{"attributes":{"bold":true},"insert":"-"},{"insert":" or "},{"attributes":{"bold":true},"insert":"+"},{"insert":".\n\nNavigating Chapters"},{"attributes":{"header":2},"insert":"\n"},{"insert":"To cycle through chapters, press "},{"attributes":{"bold":true},"insert":"CTRL"},{"insert":" + "},{"attributes":{"bold":true},"insert":"Up"},{"insert":" or "},{"attributes":{"bold":true},"insert":"Down"},{"insert":". "},{"attributes":{"bold":true},"insert":"CTRL"},{"insert":" + "},{"attributes":{"bold":true},"insert":"Right"},{"insert":" and "},{"attributes":{"bold":true},"insert":"Left"},{"insert":" will jump between the notes and main editor. These are the "},{"attributes":{"italic":true},"insert":"Navigation Keys"},{"insert":".\n\nTo move a chapter up or down in the list, press "},{"attributes":{"bold":true},"insert":"CTRL"},{"insert":" + "},{"attributes":{"bold":true},"insert":"SHIFT"},{"insert":" + "},{"attributes":{"bold":true},"insert":"Up"},{"insert":" or "},{"attributes":{"bold":true},"insert":"Down"},{"insert":". To rename a chapter, "},{"attributes":{"bold":true},"insert":"CTRL"},{"insert":" + "},{"attributes":{"bold":true},"insert":"SHIFT"},{"insert":" + "},{"attributes":{"bold":true},"insert":"Left"},{"insert":". These are the "},{"attributes":{"italic":true},"insert":"Alteration Keys"},{"insert":".\n\nFile Menu"},{"attributes":{"header":2},"insert":"\n"},{"insert":"Pressing "},{"attributes":{"bold":true},"insert":"ALT"},{"insert":" will reveal the file menu. Here you can import, export, compile, or use many other tools, all easily accessible without a mouse by navigating the menus with the "},{"attributes":{"bold":true},"insert":"Arrow Keys"},{"insert":" and "},{"attributes":{"bold":true},"insert":"Escape"},{"insert":". In addition to the usual find/replace, spellcheck, etc., there is a simple Outliner with word count breakdowns for each chapter and a fields for writing summaries.\n\nImport/Export Tools"},{"attributes":{"header":2},"insert":"\n"},{"insert":"WareWoolf makes it easy to combine multiple files, edit and style them, and export them as a document in standard manuscript format. \n\nIt is designed especially to work well for those who write first drafts in plain-text-based workflows, as is common with distraction-free writing devices such as the Astrohaus Freewrite, Alphasmart Neo, or various stripped-down applications.\n\nCompile/Export options"},{"attributes":{"header":3},"insert":"\n"},{"insert":"Currently you can compile/export your work in plain text, MarkdownFic, or .docx, with some helpful options regarding headings and chapter breaks.\n\nWareWoolf's File Format"},{"attributes":{"header":2},"insert":"\n"},{"insert":"WareWoolf saves its projects as plain text JSON files so they are both human readable and quickly parsed by Javascript. There is a primary .woolf project file, and individual .pup files for each chapter in a subdirectory.\n\tFrankenstein.woolf\n\tFrankenstein_Pups\n\t\t1.pup\n\t\t2.pup\n\t\t3.pup\n\nThe reason for doing this rather than one (more convenient) file is speed. This way, WareWoolf does not hold your entire (perhaps very long) novel in memory, but only one chapter at a time--the chapter you are viewing. \n\nPlease note that the pup files must be kept either in a subdirectory or the same directory as the project file. If you move them, WareWoolf will prompt you to show the new location at load.\n\nHelp"},{"attributes":{"header":2},"insert":"\n"},{"insert":"And of course, if you ever need help remembering a shortcut, simply remember the shortcut "},{"attributes":{"bold":true},"insert":"CTRL "},{"insert":"+ "},{"attributes":{"bold":true},"insert":"H"},{"insert":", or use the file menu to open the Help menu, and all will be revealed.\n"}]}